    name VARCHAR(100),
    namespace INTEGER(5), # REFERENCES tNamespace(NamespaceId),
    stereotype INTEGER(5), # REFERENCES tStereotype(StereotypeId),

    UMLClassName VARCHAR(100));

git-svn-id: http://argouml.tigris.org/svn/argouml/trunk@1222 a161b567-7d1e-0410-9ef9-912c70fedb3f

Hello
This is a partial src_new.zargo
I propose that condense our energies around one document. The src_new.zargo.
 This way we'd actually be using Argo and UML to develop Argo itself.
The advantages of this are many
*complicated refactoring issues could be modeled
*test models could be generated and analyzed
*limitations of Argo as a UML development environment would
quickly become evident to developers
*users would be able to benefit from seeing the development
process 'in action' as the developers work out tricky pieces of coding
*limit the 'repetition' of 'where is what and what does it do?'  questions
*document limitations in Argo in a zargo that could be used as reference for UML compliance
*model new interfaces or wizards
*Use the behavioral and structural diagrams
Proposed actions:
*Set up a src_new.zargo (this one is not complete) in the CVS
*Encourage developers to use the zargo as the starting point for discussion
of issues and solutions
*Encourage users to use the zargo for reference and for asking questions
* link directly in Argo, allowing developers/users, through the help/about,
 to download the zargo. This would be  especially nice for tutorials as we know for sure
that documentation and notes are successfully saved in zargos now.
This would definitely aid in the instruction process for new developers
and users alike and bring us all closer to the purpose of UML. To communicate complicated
coding issues/solutions in a Unified Modeling Language.
Dennis

git-svn-id: http://argouml.tigris.org/svn/argouml/trunk@1372 a161b567-7d1e-0410-9ef9-912c70fedb3f

Full issue of the user manual to support the release of ArgoUML 0.9.6. With the
exception of 3 sections in Chapter 20, the reference part of the manual
(chapters 7 through 21) is now completed.

Updated to correct description of pop-up menus for associations on class and
use case diagrams; updated fix for newly created stereotypes not appearing in
the drop down. Correct description of snooze button. Added pop-up menu
descriptions for aggregation, multiplicity and navigability of associations on
class diagrams. Completed chapters 17 (sequence diagrams), 18 (state diagrams),
19 (collaboration diagrams) and 21 (built-in datatypes, classes, interfaces and
stereotypes). Chapter 20 (deployment diagrams) has example diagrams,
description of nodes and all artifacts that are used on other diagrams as well,
but omits description of node instances, components and component instances.

Chapter 1 (introduction), tutorial chapter 2 (UML based OOA&D) and reference
chapters 7 (user interface), 8 (navigation pane), 9 (editing pane), 10 (details
pane), 11 (to-do pane), 12 (menu bar), 13 (critics), 14 (top level artifacts),
15 (use case diagrams), 16 (class diagrams), 17 (sequence diagrams), 18 (state
diagrams), 19 (collaboration diagrams) and 21 (built-in datatypes, classes,
interfaces and stereotypes) are now largely complete. Chapter 20 (deployment
diagrams) is complete apart from the description of node instances, components
and component instances.

git-svn-id: http://argouml.tigris.org/svn/argouml/trunk@1545 a161b567-7d1e-0410-9ef9-912c70fedb3f

a double click on a package in a class diagram will now either lead the user to the underlying class diagram or ask the user whether he wants to create a class diagram.

The behaviour is as follows:
The diagram is selected according to following principles:
1.  First class-diagram in package that begins with "main"
2.  First class-diagram in package
3. If no diagram exist for the package a  new class-diagram is created with standard default name prefixed with "main", ie "main_class diagram x"

git-svn-id: http://argouml.tigris.org/svn/argouml/trunk@1548 a161b567-7d1e-0410-9ef9-912c70fedb3f

Fix to naming of generalizes/generalizations and specializes/specializations on
property tabs.

Now all use "Generalizations:" to refer to UML artifacts that are
generalizations of the current UML artifact and "Specializations:" to refer to
UL artifacts that are specializations of the current UML artifact.

Meaning is now consistent across all users (actor, use case, association,
class, component, data type, interface, node, stereotype and package).


git-svn-id: http://argouml.tigris.org/svn/argouml/trunk@1549 a161b567-7d1e-0410-9ef9-912c70fedb3f

Provides a full implementation of UML Include and Extend relationships, fixing
various problems with use cases at the same time.

As part of this exercise the files involved have mostly been provided with full
JavaDoc and a "Howto" for adding new property panels and figs has been written.

This has involved the use of a property panel popup menu that can link to
existing model elements. An extension of UMLModelElementList has been provided
to do this - UMLModelElementListLink.

A simplification to providing modifier check buttons has been provided through
the new class PropPanelModifiers.

Additional GIF files, prop panels and figXXX are provided to support the new
relationships.

This provides the fix to issues 459, 460, 475, 476, 477 and 490.

git-svn-id: http://argouml.tigris.org/svn/argouml/trunk@1626 a161b567-7d1e-0410-9ef9-912c70fedb3f

Patch to make PropPanel.setNameEventListening() work. Done my implementing the
more general UMLThirdPartyEventListener class, and defining
setNameEventListening() in terms of this.

This allows property panels to track changes in third party NSUML entities that
may affect them, and thereby keep the user interface up to date.

For example this allows stereotype and type combo boxes (pop-ups) to see any
new stereotypes or classes/datatypes immediately.

This has allowed some simplification of the code in UMLComboBoxModel.java and
UMLClassifierComboBoxModel.java

Implementation of use cases with (optional) extension point
compartments. Includes support for extension points in the navigation pane, a
tool to add extension points on the use case diagram, navigation up from
extension point to owning use case (rather than owning project), style sheet
for use cases to set extension point display and context sensitive pop-up menu
for use case to set extension point display. All presentation is done through
the Notation package.

Fixes issues 784 and 794

git-svn-id: http://argouml.tigris.org/svn/argouml/trunk@1767 a161b567-7d1e-0410-9ef9-912c70fedb3f

TestArgoParser is an example of how tests can be written which verify that a
project can be loaded.

Both implemented tests fail at the moment, as one is loaded via http and is an
invalid project file, the other depends on my local hard drive.

The idea is to create a project file repository, which can be tested against,
e.g. from user submissions which test particular issues, or to enable developers to bulk test changes.

implemented deleteNamespace()

A statemachine has a classifier namspace.
Therefore, when you delete a class the above
method ensures that all owned elements of that class are deleted.
It also means that if if you now delete a package all owned elements
in that will be automatically deleted.

git-svn-id: http://argouml.tigris.org/svn/argouml/trunk@3817 a161b567-7d1e-0410-9ef9-912c70fedb3f

Refactoring of the Tree view model/perspective classes.

TreeModelSupport - provides tree event handling
PerspectiveSupport - provides support for perspective rules
TreeModelComposite - now only implements the TreeModel interface for clarity
ToDoPersptive & NavPerspective - override TreeModel methods and have spcific methods.
ToDoPane & NavigatorPane - now build the lists of Perspectives, which makes a clearer separation between a perspective and a collection of perspectives...
NavigatorConfig & Actions - updated as these are dependent classes.

eliminated duplication of code, clearer separation of functionality.

Issue number: 1739 point 2)

git-svn-id: http://argouml.tigris.org/svn/argouml/trunk@6238 a161b567-7d1e-0410-9ef9-912c70fedb3f

Changed registrateTargetListeners to use a more specific cast since
java 1.5 has changed EventListenerList.add to a template call.
It can be proven that all listeners will be of the specific type:
* Listeners are only added to the returned EventListenerList if either
  - They are TargetListeners
  - They are in a EventListenerList returned from a recursive call to this function
* Thus all listeners from the recursive call must be TargetListeners
QED

git-svn-id: http://argouml.tigris.org/svn/argouml/trunk@6356 a161b567-7d1e-0410-9ef9-912c70fedb3f

From Daniel Watrous:
- It seems that in many cases the design of a model can proceed without addressing the critic and so I chose to change the text "To fix this" to "To address this".  This seems to me more appropriate all of the time.
- Fixed various spelling errors.
- I began to re-write some of the descriptions to be more readable
- A small inconsistency throughout has to do with capitalization of nouns such as class/Class, association/Association, etc.  When referring to model elements we could choose to treat them as proper nouns and capitalize them, otherwise they should all be lower case.  So far I have chosen not to capitalize them.

    Effective immediately, licensees and distributors are no longer
    required to include the acknowledgement within advertising
    materials.  Accordingly, the foregoing paragraph of those BSD Unix
    files containing it is hereby deleted in its entirety.

    William Hoskins
    Director, Office of Technology Licensing
    University of California, Berkeley

git-svn-id: http://argouml.tigris.org/svn/argouml/trunk@8155 a161b567-7d1e-0410-9ef9-912c70fedb3f

Make bounds setting more efficient. It is more efficient to calls setBounds than to call both setSize() and setLocation(). It is more efficient to call setSize() than to call setWidth() and setHeight(). Not just that this is another method call be the fig is actually moved/resized for each bounds element if called individually rather than just once by setBounds(). This is compounded if a Fig contains child figs as the extra work is multiplied by all children that are also resized/moved.

Fixed the following problem:
1. Draw a usecase and an actor.
2. Select the usecase.
3. Drag from the toolbelt button for association on tyhe usecase a new association, and release the mouse over the actor.
As a result, the association is not attached to the head/arm or leg of the actor, but to a box around him.
You can easiest spot this when dragging the usecase around the actor.

It does work well, when you just click on the actor's toolbelt button to create an associated usecase.
The problem got corrected after save/load.

git-svn-id: http://argouml.tigris.org/svn/argouml/trunk@8759 a161b567-7d1e-0410-9ef9-912c70fedb3f

More from http://argouml-stats.tigris.org/nonav/reports/findbugs/:
Creating new instances of java.lang.Boolean wastes memory, since Boolean objects are immutable and there are only two useful values of this type. Use the Boolean.valueOf() method to create Boolean objects instead.


git-svn-id: http://argouml.tigris.org/svn/argouml/trunk@8760 a161b567-7d1e-0410-9ef9-912c70fedb3f

More from http://argouml-stats.tigris.org/nonav/reports/findbugs/:
Questionable use of non-short-circuit logic
THis code seems to be using non-short-circuit logic (e.g., & or |) rather than short-circuit logic (&& or ||). Non-short-circuit logic causes both sides of the expression to be evaluated even when the result can be inferred from knowing the left-hand side. This can be less efficient and can result in errors if the left-hand side guards cases when evaluating the right-hand side can generate an error.

Review and update of event listener usage.  Basics were done for all figures, but Edges had the most detailed review.  Nodes need additional review.

Realization, Abstraction, and Dependency were refactored to align type hierarchy with UML spec (should be invisbile to callers).

Things reviewed for/changed included:
 - use new convenience functions to register listeners
 - use removeAllListeners for unregistration where possible
 - don't re-register listeners when nothing has changed
 - check received events to make sure they are of the expected type
 - align implementations of FigNode & FigEdge so they work the same
 - use renderingChanged instead of modelChanged(null) in edges
 - using super classes methods as much as possible
 - style issues including missing Javadoc

change of import behavior: instead of exceptions when some classifier is not found, now it is dynamically generated in the model. The only issue is, that when it's not clear if it's a class or interface, then a class is generated. If this guess is wrong, then this could lead to a realization of a class, which is strange, but this seems to be no problem for the model (I tested this). Another remark: this feature is only enabled for full import, and only for the second import run.

Only change target on mouseclick.
Previously we change target on selection change but change of target changes selection. Therefore we get cyclic problems.
There was code to try and trap that cycle but I think it's not liekly to be thread safe.
This change also helps achieve issue 4500

Aligned Fig size: before, different parts of a class had width 60, but name and stereo were 90. You could see this give a special effect when drawing classes in certain cases.
In ArgoUML V0.22 the old value of 60 was changed to 90, IIRC not intentionally.
Hence, I wanted to restore the value to 60 now, but to align to grid better, it would better be a multiple of 16 (or 8). So, the final choice is 64.

git-svn-id: http://argouml.tigris.org/svn/argouml/trunk@16601 a161b567-7d1e-0410-9ef9-912c70fedb3f

Issue 1048: merging from branches/work_issue_1048_dthompson to trunk, implementing adjustment of labels on path items.
Notable changes:
* New mode at the top of the GEF mode stack: ModeLabelDrag, to handle the label drag events. The stack is reinitialised in MultiEditorPane.java.
* Switched most (all?) of the path item placement strategies to PathItemPlacement
* Selection boxes are removed for path items, and instead are highlighted in an alpha shaded blue.
* Double-clicking anywhere in the shaded area of a path item edits the first editable text box.
* Path item positions are saved to the .uml file using a modified PGML.tee.
* Path item positions are restored from the .uml file using PrivateHandler.java.
* Some tweaks to PathItemPlacement to make it position labels more reliably.
For more info, see issue 1048 and http://argouml.tigris.org/wiki/Issue1048

git-svn-id: http://argouml.tigris.org/svn/argouml/trunk@17357 a161b567-7d1e-0410-9ef9-912c70fedb3f

Corrected a potential problem located by FindBugs :

File: PriorityNode.java, Line: 70, Type: LI_LAZY_INIT_UPDATE_STATIC, Priority: High, Category: CORRECTNESS

Incorrect lazy initialization and update of static field

This method contains an unsynchronized lazy initialization of a static field. After the field is set, the object stored into that location is further accessed. The setting of the field is visible to other threads as soon as it is set. If the futher accesses in the method that set the field serve to initialize the object, then you have a very serious multithreading bug, unless something else prevents any other thread from accessing the stored object until it is fully initialized.

git-svn-id: http://argouml.tigris.org/svn/argouml/trunk@19769 a161b567-7d1e-0410-9ef9-912c70fedb3f

Fix for the part of issue 5990 that is a bug.
The part of issue 5990 that is a feature request is not fixed by this commit.
This change is to maintain a private attribute on the FigMessage to remember what kind of message is represented. This way, we do not need to query the model for this information, which is impossible during deletion of modelelements.
The use of an array of booleans is admittedly ugly, but I was looking for a quick and reliable solution.
I presumed that the Message never changes type.
